         <abstract>
            <p>Given positive integers $r_1, r_2, r_3,\ldots, r_j$ such that $$r_1 &lt; r_2 &lt; r_3 &lt; \cdots &lt; r_j &lt; m; m &gt; 1;$$ we find the number $P(n, m; R)$ of partitions of a given positive integer $n$ into parts belonging to the set $R$ of residue classes $$r_1(\operatorname{mod} m), r_2(\operatorname{mod} m),\ldots, r_j(\operatorname{mod} m).$$ This leads to an identity which is more general though less elegant then the well-known Rogers-Ramanujan identities.</p>
          </abstract>
